                      "children": [
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "id": "tiUfp",
                          "name": "canvasText",
                          "fill": "$text-primary",
                          "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                          "width": "fill_container",
                          "content": "The regulatory landscape for artificial intelligence is shifting rapidly across the world's major economic blocs, revealing fundamentally different philosophies about the relationship between technological innovation and governmental oversight.\n\nDistinct frameworks have crystallized in the past eighteen months. The European Union's AI Act, adopted in March 2024, establishes the world's first comprehensive risk-based classification system. High-risk applications — from biometric identification in critical infrastructure management — face mandatory conformity assessments, while general-purpose AI models must meet transparency obligations that scale with their systemic influence.\n\nThe United States has taken a markedly different path. Executive Order 14110, signed in October 2023, expresses the EU's prescriptive categorization in favor of safety testing mandates and voluntary commitments from frontier AI developers. The approach reflects a philosophical preference for industry self-governance, tempered by federal oversight at the frontier of capability.\n\nChina's regulatory architecture, meanwhile, has evolved through a series of targeted regulations — on algorithmic recommendations (2023), deep synthesis (2023), and generative AI services (2023). Rather than a single omnibus law, Beijing has constructed a layered system that prioritizes content governance and social stability alongside innovation promotion.",
                          "lineHeight": 1.8,
                          "fontFamily": "$font-mono",
                          "fontSize": 13,
                          "fontWeight": "normal"
                        }
                      ]
